<TITLE> Whatmore leaves Friday </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 31 (bdnews24.com)  Outgoing Bangladesh coach Dav Whatmore leaves Friday noon here for Australia with "a lot of sweet memories and good photographs" with the Tigers in his four years stint. "I am leaving with a lot of sweet memories and good photographs with the boys," Whatmore told bdnews24.com Thursday by phone. The Sri Lanka-born Australian took the reins of Bangladesh after the disastrous campaign in the 2003 World Cup. His contract with Bangladesh Cricket Board (BCB) expired after the 2007 World Cup in the West Indies. The 53-year old, however, agreed to be with the Tigers for the just-concluded home series against India. Whatmore courted controversy during the World Cup when he had expressed desire to become India's coach. The BCB top-brass Thursday afternoon threw a farewell party in his honour at its head office at Gulshan. The country's most affluent board gave him two memosthe Tigers' World Cup shirt and a bat autographed by Test cricketers of Bangladesh and Zimbabwe during Bangladesh's tour of Zimbabwe where the Tigers tasted their first-ever Test triumph. Skipper Habibul Bashar handed the World Cup shirt to Whatmore. Whatmore who had won the World Cup with Sri Lanka in 1996, guided Bangladesh to the second round of the cricket's showcase event in the West Indies with two stunning win over India and South Africa. The team also won against Australia and Sri Lanka under his coaching. Bangladesh have won 33 of 90 one-day internationals they have played under Whatmore. In 27 Tests under his tutelage, Bangladesh have drawn four against West Indies, Zimbabwe and India and won once. bdn
